'''John Cordes''' (1890 - ?) was a [[detective]] in the [[New York Police Department]], once described by New York mayor [[Jimmy Walker]] as "the city's best cop".<ref name="Krajicek" /> He is the only detective to win the department's [[New York City Police Department Medal of Honor|Medal of Honor]] twice.

Cordes first won the medal in 1923 after coming across a [[Manhattan]] cigar store robbery in progress. As a result of his involvement, Cordes suffered five [[gunshot]] wounds, three of which came from another policeman for unknown reasons.<ref name="Krajicek">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/justice-story/nypd-bruise-forced-confession-kills-case-ends-3rd-degree-beatings-article-1.1254067|title=NYPD detective forces murder confession, but state Supreme Court sets aside Joseph Barbato's conviction and puts an end to police use of third-degree beatings   - NY Daily News|last=KRAJICEK|first=DAVID J.|work=nydailynews.com|access-date=2018-05-08|language=en-US}}</ref>

His second Medal of Honor was awarded in 1927 for his work in solving the kidnapping of real estate tycoon [[Abraham Scharlin]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=2bPTBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA138&lpg=PA138&dq=%22John+Cordes%22+detective&source=bl&ots=oDg79_4fS_&sig=--46O_Wwvhojo-7biIZvBKijyvY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiW5O31iPfaAhWqslkKHaMTCMoQ6AEIUTAJ#v=onepage&q=cordes&f=false|title=The NYPD's First Fifty Years: Politicians, Police Commissioners, and Patrolmen|last=Whalen|first=Bernard|last2=Whalen|first2=Jon|date=2015-01-15|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc.|year=|isbn=9781612346564|location=|pages=139|language=en}}</ref>

Cordes retired in 1949.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} Part of his career is described in the book "NYPD: Stories of Survival from the Worlds Toughest Beat".{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}

