The '''Jumma people''' ({{lang-bn|জুম্ম জনগোষ্ঠী}}) is a collective term for the [[indigenous peoples]] of the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]] region of present-day [[Bangladesh]]. They include the [[Chakma people|Chakma]], [[Rakhine people|Arakanese]] (Rakhine), [[Marma people|Marma]], [[Tripuri people|Tripuri]], [[Tanchangya people|Tanchangya]], [[Chak people|Chak]], [[Pankho people|Pankho]], [[Mru]], [[Bawm]], [[Lushai]], [[Khyang people|Khyang]], [[Gurkha]], [[Assamese people|indigenous Assamese]], [[Jalia Kaibarta|Keot (Kaibarta)]], [[Santal]], and [[Khumi people|Khumi]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Van Schendel|first=Willem|title=Identity Politics in Central Asia and the Muslim World |year=2001|publisher=I.B.Tauris |isbn=978-1860642616 |page=141 |editor=Willem van Schendel, Erik J. Zurcher}}</ref>
The name ''jumma'' ("''jum'' farmer") is derived from ''jum'' cultivation, or [[slash-and-burn]] farming.<ref>{{cite book|last=Roy|first=Rajkumari Chandra Kalindi|title=Land Rights of the Indigenous Peoples of the Chittagong Hill Tracts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UQShJjSoF-MC&pg=PA28|year=2000|publisher=IWGIA|isbn=978-87-90730-29-1|page=28}}</ref> It is a [[reappropriate]]d term originally used by outsiders.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ghanea-Hercock|first1=Nazila|last2=Xanthaki|first2=Alexandra|last3=Thornberry|first3=Patrick|title=Minorities, Peoples and Self-determination|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gkupctPeacEC&pg=PA115 |year=2005|publisher=Martinus Nijhoff Publishers|isbn=90-04-14301-7|page=115|quote= It differentiates them from their plains neighbours and was initially used in a derogatory manner.}}</ref> They are also known as ''Pahari'', which simply means "hill people".<ref>{{cite book|author=International Labour Office|title=Traditional occupations of indigenous and tribal peoples: Emerging trends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_84Gg-o5BhYC&pg=PA78|year=2000 |publisher=International Labour Organization| isbn=978-92-2-112258-6|page=78}}</ref>
The Jummas are native people, unrelated to [[Bengali language|Bangla]] spoken by [[ethnic Bengali]]s. Religiously they are distinct as well, most being Buddhist, some Hindu and some are Christianized, with only a small number having converted to Islam. In addition, they have retained some traditional religious practices.<ref>{{cite book|last=Samaddar|first=Ranabir|title=Refugees and the State: Practices of Asylum and Care in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4cuGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA251|date=2003-07-04|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-81-321-0377-6|page=251}}</ref>
==Persecution by Bengalis== {{See also|Persecution of indigenous peoples in Bangladesh|2012 Ramu violence|Persecution of Buddhists}}
In 1971, following the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] in which Bangladesh achieved independence, the country's majority [[Bengali Muslims]] began strategically colonising the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT), which has displaced the Jumma people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://asaa.asn.au/ethnic-violence-bangladesh-assault-minority-peoples-continues/|title=Ethnic violence in Bangladesh: assault on minority peoples continues - Asian Studies Association of Australia|date=2017-08-02|work=Asian Studies Association of Australia|access-date=2018-09-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> Between 1978 and 1984, the government incentivised over 400,000 Bengali Muslims to settle in the CHT, by offering each family 5 acres of land and free food rations.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=|title=Nationalism and Intra-State Conflicts in the Postcolonial World|last=I|first=Fonkem Achankeng|date=2015-09-28|publisher=Lexington Books|year=|isbn=9781498500265|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> Between 1979 and 1997, Bengali Muslim settlers and the Bangladesh military carried out over 15 major massacres of Buddhist peoples in the CHT.<ref name=":0" /> Due to the outbreaks of violence, communal and social unrest, many fled to the Indian states of Mizoram and Tripura, or to Burma (now Myanmar).<ref name=":0" /> The Bangladesh government has also forcibly converted Marmas from Buddhism to Islam and destroyed Buddhist temples ([[kyaung]]), as means of integrating them into Bangladeshi society.<ref name=":0" /> [[Amnesty International]] reports document systematic accounts of torture and extrajudicial executions of tribal inhabitants of the Chittagong Hill Tracts by security forces during 1989 and 1990.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/196000/asa130091991en.pdf|title=Human rights violations in the Chittagong Hill Tracts: An update|last=|first=|date=1991-09-13|website=Amnesty International|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-18}}</ref>
[[Human Rights Watch]] has consistently reported that "indigenous groups in the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) have for decades faced discrimination, forced displacement, assaults, evictions, and destruction of property by both Bangladeshi security forces and Bengali settlers from the mainland.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2018/country-chapters/bangladesh#807546|title=World Report 2018: Rights Trends in Bangladesh|date=2017-12-14|work=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2017/country-chapters/bangladesh#807546|title=World Report 2017: Rights Trends in Bangladesh|date=2017-01-12|work=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref> Bengali settlers and soldiers have raped native Jumma (Chakma) women "with impunity" with the Bangladeshi security forces doing little to protect the Jummas and instead assisting the rapists and settlers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.survivalinternational.org/news/10141|title=Chittagong Hill Tracts of Bangladesh – rapists act with impunity|last1=McEvoy|first1=Mark|last2=|first2=|date=3 April 2014|website=Survival International - The movement for tribal peoples|publisher=|access-date=|quote=}}</ref> In June 2017, Bengali rioters burned 100 indigenous homes in [[Langadu Upazila|Langadu]], reportedly even as army and police looked on.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/spotlight/the-run-1417459|title=Longadu burning|date=2017-06-09|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref>
