{{Infobox language |name = Krevinian |altname = Krevin |states = [[Latvia]] |extinct = 19th century |ref = |familycolor = Uralic |fam2 = [[Finnic languages|Finnic]] |fam3 = [[Votic language|Votic]] |iso3 = zkv |linglist = zkv |glotto=none }}
'''Krevinian''', or '''Krevin''', is an extinct dialect of the [[Votic language]], spoken in Latvia until the 1800s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=39vRAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA64|title=Universal Geography: Or A Description of All Parts of the World, on a New Plan, According to the Great Natural Divisions of the Globe|last=Malte-Brun|first=Conrad|date=1829|publisher=A. Finley|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=64|language=en}}</ref> It was spoken in the city of [[Bauska|Bauske]], in [[Courland|Kurland]] (now spelt Bauska and Courland).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WubvXTkjoLUC&pg=PA11|title=An Introduction to the Uralic Languages|last=Collinder|first=Björn|date=1975|publisher=University of California Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=11|language=en}}</ref>
